text:
I sing of faith, and of readiness;
for Life and Nature are not vast in what they are only now,
but greater still in what is still to come,
and from that equation I sing for you.

What flock like Russell told its tale;  
His voice was heard o’er moor and dale,  
He knew the Lord’s own sheep, each tail,  
Across the height;  
And saw whether they were sick or hale,  
At first clear sight.

source_text:
What herd like Russell tell’d his tale;
His voice was heard thro’ muir and dale,
He kenn’d the Lord’s sheep, ilka tail,
Owre a’ the height;
An’ saw gin they were sick or hale,
At the first sight.

text:
’Twad be owre lang a tale to tell,
How mony a story’s past;
And how they throng’d unto the yill,
When they were a’ dismiss’d;
How drink went round, in cogs and caups,
Amang the furms and benches;
And cheese and bread, frae women’s laps,
Were dealt in lunches
And dawds that day.

